<paragraph id="8B9E36DBFF917744FF7EBE4669418481" blockId="29.[151,1437,328,965]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis id="B955EAC9FF917744FF7EBE466CDE8455" bold="true" box="[199,496,544,569]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Comparative discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C214D58FF917744FE42BE476F848455" box="[507,682,545,569]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Planariidae" genus="Polycelis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="nigra">
<emphasis id="B955EAC9FF917744FE42BE476F848455" box="[507,682,545,569]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Polycelis nigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of the most widespread freshwater planarians in Europe. However, it is extremely scarce in the Iberian Peninsula (
<figureCitation id="131A2A5EFF917744FC99BE236E4A8431" box="[800,868,581,605]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1558,1581]" captionTargetBox="[171,1436,828,1523]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,828,1528]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Distributional records of twelve species of freshwater planarians in the Iberian Peninsula. Data from De Beauchamp, 1920; De Beauchamp, 1932; Baguñà et al. 1980, 81; Gourbault, 1981; Ribas, 1990; Sluys et al. 1995; Carranza &amp; Giribet, 1997; unpublished records, this study." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/206801/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
Fig. 
<number id="3DE924FCFF917744FCECBE236E4A8431" box="[853,868,581,605]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
), where it had only been found in the basin of the river Muga, Girona Province (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB04B2AFF917744FE50BE0F6FEF84ED" author="Baguna" box="[489,705,617,641]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refString="Baguna, J., Salo, E. &amp; Romero, R. (1980) Les planaries d'aigues dolces a Catalunya i les illes Balears. 1. Clau sistematica i distribucio geografica. Butlleti de la Institucio Catalana d'Historia Natural, 45, 15 - 30." type="journal article" year="1980">
Baguñà 
<emphasis id="B955EAC9FF917744FDFEBE0C6F5184ED" box="[583,639,617,641]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">et al.</emphasis>
1980
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB04B2AFF917744FD72BE0F6E2984ED" author="Baguna" box="[715,775,617,641]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" refString="Baguna, J., Salo, E. &amp; Romero, R. (1981) Biogeografia de las planarias de aguas dulces (Platelminthes; Turbellaria; Tricladida; Paludicola) en Espana. Datos preliminares. Actas del Primer Congreso de la Sociedad Espanola de Limnologia, 265 - 280." type="book chapter" year="1981">1981</bibRefCitation>
). We collected the species from five new Iberian localities: Galicia (three localities), Asturias (one locality, northwestern 
<collectingCountry id="F336764BFF917744FCF5BEEB6EA084C9" box="[844,910,653,677]" name="Spain" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Spain</collectingCountry>
) and Girona (one locality, northeastern 
<collectingCountry id="F336764BFF917744FAF5BEEB68BF84C9" box="[1356,1425,653,677]" name="Spain" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Spain</collectingCountry>
). Animals from Asturias reproduce sexually, as is usual in this species. The egg capsules are covered with a hemispherical envelope formed by a transparent, gelatinous or mucous substance (
<figureCitation id="131A2A5EFF917744FC43BEB369658481" box="[1018,1099,725,749]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1368,1391]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1010,1344]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[151,1436,1010,1344]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 18. Polycelis nigra, (A) egg capsule from a laboratory population originating from animals collected from the river Uncín near the beach of Concha de Artedo (Asturias, northern Spain), (B – C) specimen from the river Muga (Girona, northeastern Spain), (B) adult worm encysted, (C) adult worm at the moment of being forced to leave its envelope." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/206815/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
Fig. 
<number id="3DE924FCFF917744FB96BEB369658481" box="[1071,1099,725,749]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="18.0">18</number>
</figureCitation>
A).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9E36DBFF917744FF7CBE9F6E8C85A9" blockId="29.[151,1437,328,965]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
After a period of starvation at 
<number id="3DE924FCFF917744FDAFBE9F6F1C857D" box="[534,562,761,785]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="21.0">21</number>
Cº in the laboratory, several specimens from the river Muga (that belongs to a previously known population) enveloped themselves in a transparent, oval-shaped capsule (
<figureCitation id="131A2A5EFF917744FB10BF7B69D58559" box="[1193,1275,797,821]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1368,1391]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1010,1344]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[151,1436,1010,1344]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 18. Polycelis nigra, (A) egg capsule from a laboratory population originating from animals collected from the river Uncín near the beach of Concha de Artedo (Asturias, northern Spain), (B – C) specimen from the river Muga (Girona, northeastern Spain), (B) adult worm encysted, (C) adult worm at the moment of being forced to leave its envelope." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/206815/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
Fig. 
<number id="3DE924FCFF917744FB67BF7B69D58559" box="[1246,1275,797,821]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="18.0">18</number>
</figureCitation>
B), apparently formed by secretions of their own mucus. The planarians were completely inactive inside the capsule. When forced to leave their envelope (
<number id="3DE924FCFF917744FE1EBF036CEA8511" box="[423,452,869,893]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="18.0">18</number>
C), the worms returned to their normal active condition. The gelatinous envelope of the egg capsules as well as the envelope observed in encysted adult specimens suggest that Iberian populations of 
<taxonomicName id="4C214D58FF917744FA3EBFEC6DFA85A9" class="Rhabditophora" family="Planariidae" genus="Polycelis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Seriata" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="nigra">
<emphasis id="B955EAC9FF917744FA3EBFEC6DFA85A9" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">P. nigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have developed forms of resistance to desiccation or starvation.
</paragraph>
